## 1\. Use Case {#1.-use-case}

Professional communication is an essential part in our day to day life. However, often emotion gets the best of us. We write messages often in a passive aggressive or angry or confused tone. Such messages can greatly thwart collaborations, goodwill.

We are what we speak. So it is necessary to keep our tone and words in check. That is why we present our tool “**Tone Assistant**”. With this tool, users can write their message and before sending it, they can check the tone of the message and rephrase it if necessary.

## 2\. Defining the LLM Models {#2.-defining-the-llm-models}

We use two models for our project.

| Use case | Model Name | Parameters | Comments |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Message tone analysis | Fine-Tuned BERT | 343.3 million  | Faster and 0 cost  |
| Rephrasing message | gpt-3.5-turbo | 20b | Cheaper alternative to gpt-4o |

The reason for the difference is that the message tone analysis task will be executed a lot when a user is texting with someone. So it is necessary to make it faster and cheaper. So we provide a locally deployed fine tuned LLM for tone analysis.

On the other hand, rephrasing message tasks is expected to be less frequent, unless the person is having a very fake conversion with someone. Fake conversations are less frequent and quality matters in those few cases. So we use gpt-3.5-turbo. It ensures high quality while being overall low cost due to low usage.

## 3\. Dataset Preparation {#3.-dataset-preparation}

We use airline complaints tweets dataset. The dataset contains 1700 positive and 1700 negative sentiment tweets. The dataset can be found in [this publicly shared drive](https://drive.google.com/uc?export=download&id=1wHt8PsMLsfX5yNSqrt2fSTcb8LEiclcf).  
![][image2]

To process the data, we remove twitter account names e.g. @united in above picture since they have no effect on the sentiment of a tweet. Additionally, we remove any trailing spaces and @ signs.  
![][image3]

## 4\. Model Training {#4.-model-training}

### 4.1 Fine-Tuning BERT {#4.1-fine-tuning-bert}

We take a 30-70 test-train split to train our dataset.  
![][image4]  
We use pretrained model **bert-base-uncased.**  We use a tokenizer corresponding to this model to tokenize our dataset. The max token length is 128\. Because Bert was trained on 128 tokens sequence 90% of the time. So it has more generalization and performance on shorter sequences of length 128 tokens at most. While max 512 token limit exists, Bert was trained on long sequences only 10% of time. This is to reduce computational cost and time needed.  
![][image5]

We now define BertForSequenceClassification with 2 output neurons. Since we want either positive or negative output.  
![][image6]

We use checkpointing to ensure that progress is not lost irrespective of any issue we might encounter.  
![][image7]  
We save progress after each epoch. We were limited to a total of 3 epochs due to time limitation. Our model finally had a validation accuracy of 81% which is quite satisfactory for our task at hand.   
![][image8]

We finally save our model for using it locally. 

### 4.2 Gpt-3.5-turbo API usage {#4.2-gpt-3.5-turbo-api-usage}

We access gpt-3.5-turbo through their api endpoint. We do prompt engineering through a simple command of the following:

TASK \= "You are an email message processor. Given an email message and an emotion, you will update the email according to the emotion."  
prompt \= f"Email: {request.email}\\nEmotion: {request.emotion}"

The API returns a rephrased email content based on the emotion.

## 5\. User Guide {#5.-user-guide}

### 5.1 Installation {#5.1-installation}

Ideally, it will be a website that users can simply browse. But if they wish to host it locally, they simply need to download the codebase and execute the following commands.

\> pip install \-r requirements.txt  
\> uvicorn server:app –reload

### 5.2 Usage {#5.2-usage}

Since Tone Assistant is just an auxiliary tool in users’ daily workflow, we keep the GUI minimal.  
![][image9]  
The above usage scenario can be described as following:

1. The user will write their email or message in the textbox.  
2. They will click on “**Analyze Sentiment**”  
3. If the sentiment does not align with their goal, they can choose to rephrase the message.  
4. Select any emotion e.g. Happy to which the message tone will transform into  
5. Click “**Rephrase Message**” to get a rephrased message with a Happy tone.

## 6\. Future Works {#6.-future-works}

This tool can be seamlessly integrated with the user's workflow much like grammarly. Additionally, the AI assistant can keep a map of the user's relationships to automatically infer what tone the user should prefer when writing a message. Additionally, to ensure personalization, the AI should learn the user's writing style and try to mimic it as much as possible.
